						( recreandus. Singula
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						viuid&egrave;,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						( viuidissim&egrave;.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				You must either read things intelligently or perform deeds seriously,
				either make the body strong through exercise, or recreate the mind through pleasant activity.
				Singular things vigorously, most vigorously.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nemo adhuc nouit
						vti Seipso, aut 
						tempore.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Until now, no one has known how to enjoy either himself or time.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Artibus infiniti sunt
						abusi: nemo vsus.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Infinite are the men who misuse the arts; no man uses them. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Vivum coeli, terra[e]q[ue] globum nondu[m] vidi.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				I have not yet seen a lively band of the heavens and earth.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Alia nulla creatura mel ex floribus
						potest exugere, pra[e]ter Apem.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				No other creature can suck out the honey from flowers better than the bee.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Solius anima[e]
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						mirabilior virtus attractiua, qu&agrave;m Magnetis.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The attractive virtue of the soul alone is more wondrous than that of a magnet.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Quicquid est vnum, Politicum sit alterum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Whatever one thing is, let the other be political. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Tempus perditur, quod non viuid&egrave;, valid&egrave;q[ue] inseruit uel
						Animo, uel Corpori, uel Fortuna[e]. Et preciosum est,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						quicquid horum alicui conducit.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Time is lost when it is not devoted vigorously and powerfully to mind, body, or fortune.
				And whatever of these things is useful to anyone is rewarding.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
